During the grant period, I published six articles based on my grant research in highly ranked refereed mathematics journals.  One additional article has been submitted and is currently under review, and two articles are still being prepared for submission.  The common theme in all of this research is the application of geometric techniques to study structural features of differential equations.  This approach, pioneered in the early 20th century by Elie Cartan, has enjoyed great success in furthering the understanding of many types of differential equations and their solutions.

The primary grant project centered around the local existence problem for isometric embedding of higher-dimensional Riemannian manifolds into Euclidean space.  In joint work with G.-Q. Chen, M. Slemrod, D. Wang, and D. Yang, we achieved one of the major objectives of the project: we proved a local existence theorem for solutions of a category of systems of partial differential equations that we call "strongly symmetric positive."  We then applied this theorem to give a vastly simplified proof of earlier results of Bryant-Griffiths-Yang and Nakamura-Maeda regarding the local existence of isometric embeddings of smooth 3-dimensional Riemannian manifolds into 6-dimensional Euclidean space.  We expect that our theorem will have broader applications to other problems in geometry and differential equations.

Four of the research articles published during the grant period were joint projects with current and former undergraduate and masters-level independent study students.  These projects include:

1) a classification of lightlike surfaces in 3-dimensional Minkowski space, including the construction of explicit examples (joint with B. Carlsen) - see example in Image 1;

2) a comparison of two notions for arc length for curves in surfaces in 3-dimensional equi-affine space, including a classification of those curves for which the two notions agree (joint with E. Estrada, M. May, J. Miller, S. Paneyra, and M. Schmidt) - see example in Image 2;

3) a classification of hyperbolic affine flat, affine minimal surfaces in 3-dimensional equi-affine space, including the construction of explicit examples (joint with J. Miller) - see example in Image 3;

4) a computation of a complete set of local invariants for 2-dimensional surfaces in 5-dimensional centro-affine space, together with a classification of the surfaces in this category that have maximal symmetry, including the construction of explicit examples (joint with N. Bushek) - see 3-dimensional projection of an example in Image 4;

In addition to these research articles, I completed a manuscript for a graduate textbook on Cartan's method of moving frames.  The manuscript has been submitted to the American Mathematical Society and is currently under review.

Finally, during the grant period I co-organized a research conference, "New Directions in Exterior Differential Systems: a conference in honor of Robert Bryant's 60th birthday."  This week-long conference brought together researchers and students in the field of exterior differential systems and featured talks on a wide array of current research in the field.




